analyte_name: Volume, CEC, NH4OAc, Syringe Extract, 2M KCl displacement
analyte_desc: The volume of the extract contained in the syrringe of the CEC procedure. This value is not normally reported.  It is used in the calculation of extractable bases (Ca, Mg, Na, K).
The KCl extractable iron approximates the exchangeable or plant available fraction. It is reported as milligrams per kilogram on a <2 mm base.
NH4OAC extractable sodium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable Na. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base.
NH4OAC extractable potassium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable K. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base.
NH4OAC extractable magnesium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable Mg if MgCO3 is not present. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base.

CEC by NH4OAC is the cation exchange capacity of the sample, determined by 1N NH4OAC in a system highly buffered at pH 7.0 The NH4 is displaced by 2M KCl to obtain a solution without solids. It is reported as meq per 100 grams sample, on a <2 mm base.

NH4OAC extractable calcium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable Ca. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base. It is not reported for samples containing carbonates or soluble salts.

This ratio is calculated by CEC_NH4/Clay. It provides an index to clay activity, and allows inferences about clay mineralogy, the contribution of clay to the exchange capacity, and solution chemistry to be made.

The ratio of 15 bar H2O percent / clay percent is calculated by (W15AD or W15FM)/CLAY_TOT, reported as grams per gram, on a <2 mm base. It provides inferences about clay mineralogy and the effectiveness of dispersion in the particle size analysis.

Sodium pyrophosphate extractable aluminum is the fraction extracted by 0.1M sodium pyrophosphate. It was originally considered the portion associated with organic compounds, although subsequent evidence indicates other forms are also removed.
The KCl extractable manganese approximates the exchangeable or plant available fraction. It is reported as milligrams per kilogram on a <2 mm base.

KCl extractable aluminum approximates the exchangeable Al, and is a measure of the active acidity present in soils with a 1:1 water pH less than 5.5. It relates to the immediate lime requirement and the CEC of the soil.
Dithionite citrate extractable silica is considered an indicator of the amount of amorphous or more readily soluble silica. It is reported as gravimetric % on a <2 mm base.
Dithionite citrate extractable manganese is considered easily reducible manganese. It is reported as gravimetric percent on a <2 mm base. Values >0.2% are rare.

Dithionite citrate extractable iron is considered a general measure of total pedogenic iron. It provides inferences on the amount of iron in various forms, P fixing potential, aggregate stability, and degree of weathering. Reported as grav % on <2mm.
Dithionite citrate extractable aluminum is an indicator of the amount of aluminum substituted for iron in iron oxides. It does not necessarily represent total pedogenic Al.
The amount of ammonium oxalate extractable silica relates to the amount of allophane and imogolite in andic materials. It is reported as a gravimetric percent on a <2 mm base.
Phosphorus extracted with ammonium oxalate
The ammonium oxalate extractable manganese is assumed to be the fraction held in noncrystalline compounds. It is reported as milligrams per kilogram on a <2 mm base.

Ammonium oxalate extractable iron is considered a measure of the noncrystalline Fe in soils. It provides some inferences of the amount of Fe in various forms. It is reported as gravimetric % on a <2mm base.

Ammonium  oxalate extractable aluminum is an estimate of the total pedogenic Al, much of which may be in noncrystalline materials or complexed by organic matter. It is reported as gravimetric percent on a <2 mm base.
Total carbon is a measure of all organic and inorganic nitrogen, including that found in organic minerals.

Carbonate in the 2-20mm fraction is measured by CO2 evolution after acid treatment. It is reported as gravimetric percent CaCO3 on a 2-20 mm base, even though carbonates of Mg, Na, K, and Fe may be present and react with the acid.

The Olsen extractable phosphorus is used as an indicator of available phosphorus in calcareous soil materials (pH >6).

The New Zealand phosphorus retention is the gravimetric percent phosphorus removed from a solution by equilibration with a sample. It is reported on a <2 mm base. High P retention indicates andic material.
The phosphorus extractable by citric acid is an indicator of available phosphorus in the sample, reported as milligrams per kilogram on a <2 mm base.
This is the phosphorus extractable by the Bray-2  method, reported as milligrams per kilogram on a <2 mm base. Bray-2 extracts both adsorbed and easily acid-soluble forms of P.
This is the phosphorus extractable by the Bray-1 method, reported as milligrams per kilogram on a <2 mm base. It is used as an index of plant-available phosphorus. Bray-1 extracts adsorbed P.
The water soluble phosphorus is the fraction extracted by distilled water. It represents an attempt to approximate the P concentration in the soil solution, i.e. the mobile P.
The pH, 1:1 soil-water suspension is the pH of a sample measured in distilled water at a 1:1 soil:solution ratio. If wider ratios increase the pH, salts are indicated.
The oxidized pH is the pH of a sample measured after incubation while saturated with distilled water. It is normally used to indicate the acid producing potential of acid sulfate materials.
The pH, 1:50 soil-NaF suspension is the pH of a sample measured in 1.0N NaF at a 1:50 soil:solution ratio. If PH_NAF is > 9.4, andic materials are indicated.

analyte_name: Ratio, Sum of Cations to Clay, <2mm, CMS derived value default, standard pr
analyte_desc: The CEC-8.2 / total clay ratio is calculated by CEC_SUM/CLAY_TOT. It factors pH dependent charge into the inferences from CEC7_CLY. It is reported on a <2 mm base. CMS derived value default

analyte_name: Ratio, CEC NH4OAc/Clay, <2mm, CMS derived value default, standard prep
analyte_desc: This ratio is calculated by CEC_NH4/Clay. It provides an index to clay activity, and allows inferences about clay mineralogy, the contribution of clay to the exchange capacity, and solution chemistry to be made.

analyte_name: Cation Exchange Capacity, Sum of Cations, CMS default, standard prep
analyte_desc: This is the calculated CEC at pH 8.2. It is calculated by (BASE_SUM+ACID_TEA). It is reported as meq per 100 grams sample on a <2 mm base. CMS derived value default
The cumulative gravimetric percentage of particles with <0.3 mm diameter, reported on a <3 inch base.
Estimated soil organic carbon. Total carbon minus .13 X CaCO3

analyte_name: Base Saturation, NH4OAc, pH 7.0, CMS derived value default, standard prep
analyte_desc: NH4OAC base saturation (pH 7.0) is calculated by (BASE_SUM/CEC_NH4)*100.. CMS derived value default

analyte_name: Base Saturation, Sum of Cations, pH 8.2, CMS default, standard prep
analyte_desc: Base saturation by sum of cations (pH 8.2) is calculated by (BASE_SUM/CEC_SUM)*100. CMS derived value default

analyte_name: Sum of NH4OAc Extractable Bases, CMS derived value default, standard prep
analyte_desc: The sum of NH4OAC extractable bases is calculated as (CA_NH4+MG_NH4+NA_NH4+K_NH4). It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base. CMS derived value default

analyte_name: Aluminum Saturation, CMS derived value default, standard prep
analyte_desc: Aluminum saturation is calculated by (AL_KCL/(Sum of bases))*100. It provides some inference of potential Al toxicity problems, although many other factors influence Al toxicity.CMS derived value default
CMS analyte. Medium + coarse + ver coarse sand is the soil separate with 0.25 to 2 mm particle diameter. It is reported as a gravimetric percent on a <2 mm base.
The weight of the air-dry bulk sample before any other processing occurs.
The weight of the sieved coarse fragments after air-drying which are 5 to 20 mm.
The weight of coarse fragments sieved after air-drying which are 20 to 75 mm.
The weight of the 2 to 5 mm aggregates remaining after slaking.
The weight of the subsample, 2 to 5 mm, before slaking.
The weight of the sieved coarse fragments after air-drying which are 2 to 5 mm.
The weight of coarse fragments sieved after air-drying which are > 75 mm.
The field water content of a bulk sample, <2mm is the gravimetric water content of a sample, as collected. It is reported as percent gravimetric water on a <2 mm base.
The gravimetric percentage of 2 to 5 mm diameter particles slaking.
Bulk density, 1/3 bar is estimated when no measured value exists. It has been estimated from rupture resistance, particle size distribution, and organic carbon.
1/3 bar water rewet is the gravimetric percent water in clods after air drying when equilibrated at 1/3 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.
1/3 bar water before rewet is the gravimetric percent water in clods after air drying when equilibrated at 1/3 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.

Bulk density, 1/3 bar rewet (organic soils) is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume being measured after samples have been equilibrated at 1/3 bar water tension, air dried, and re-equilibrated at 1/3 bar tension.

analyte_name: Bulk Density, 1/3 Bar, Before Rewet (Organic Soils)
analyte_desc: Bulk density, 1/3 bar rewet (organic soils) is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume being measured after samples have been equilibrated at 1/3 bar water tension, air dried, and re-equilibrated at 1/3 bar tension.

Bulk density, oven dry (105 C) is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume measured on oven dry (105 C) natural fabric (clods). It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.

analyte_name: Bulk Density, Clod, Field Water Content
analyte_desc: Bulk density, <2mm fraction, moist is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume measured at field (sampling) moisture on natural clods. It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.

analyte_name: Bulk Density, Core, <2 mm fraction, Field Moist
analyte_desc: Bulk density, <2mm fraction, field moist is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume measured at field (sampling) moisture. Measurements are made on known volume cores. It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter, <2 mm base.
The effective cation exchange capacity is calculated by BASE_SUM+AL_KCL. It is not calculated if soluble salts are present. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base.

This ratio is calculated by CEC_NH4/Clay. It provides an index to clay activity, and allows inferences about clay mineralogy, the contribution of clay to the exchange capacity, and solution chemistry to be made.
Aluminum saturation is calculated by (AL_KCL/(Sum of bases))*100. It provides some inference of potential Al toxicity problems, although many other factors influence Al toxicity.

analyte_name: Ratio, Total Carbon to Nitrogen, Elementar, S prep
analyte_desc: The carbon to nitrogen ratio is calculated by C_TOT_NCS/N_TOT_NCS. It provides information related to soil fertility and the state of organic matter decomposition. It is reported on a <2 mm base.

The volume of the extract contained in the syrringe of the CEC procedure. This value is not normally reported.  It is used in the calculation of extractable bases (Ca, Mg, Na, K).
NH4OAC extractable sodium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable Na. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base.
NH4OAC extractable potassium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable K. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base.
NH4OAC extractable magnesium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable Mg if MgCO3 is not present. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base.
CEC by NH4OAC is the cation exchange capacity of the sample, determined by 1N NH4OAC in a system highly buffered at pH 7.0. It is reported as meq per 100 grams sample, on a <2 mm base.

NH4OAC extractable calcium is the fraction removed by pH 7.0 NH4OAC. It is assumed to represent the exchangeable Ca. It is reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base. It is not reported for samples containing carbonates or soluble salts.
The volume of the extract contained in the syrringe of the CEC procedure. This value is not normally reported.  It is used in the calculation of extractable bases (Ca, Mg, Na, K).
The neutral salt extractable sodium is the fraction removed by 1.0N NH4Cl.
The neutral salt extractable potassium is the fraction removed by 1.0N NH4Cl.
The neutral salt extractable magnesium is the fraction removed by 1.0N NH4Cl.

CEC by a neutral unbuffered salt (1N NH4Cl) is a measure of the neutral salt exchange capacity of the soil at its natural pH, reported as meq per 100 grams on a <2 mm base. For noncalcareous soils this value approximates (BASE_SUM+AL_KCL).
The neutral salt extractable calcium is the fraction removed by 1.0N NH4Cl.

Sodium pyrophosphate extractable manganese is the fraction extracted by 0.1M sodium pyrophosphate. It was originally considered the portion associated with organic compounds, although subsequent evidence indicates other forms are also removed.
Sodium pyrophosphate extractable iron is assumed to be the fraction associated with organic complexes. It is reported as gravimetric percent on a <2 mm base.
Sodium pyrophosphate extractable carbon was originally thought to correspond to carbon that bound Fe and Al in spodic materials. It is reported on a <2 mm base.

The pre-processed weight of the bulk sample, before any preparation work is done.  The value of this weight is used in lieu of the actual field moist sample weight to make estimates of field moisture.
The weight of the bulk sample used to prepare the air-dried sample.  This weight may be different from the self moist weight, because a subsample may have been taken for a moist preparation.
Field H20 content by core is the field water content of the material from a core bulk density determination. It is reported as percent gravimetric water on a <2 mm base.

analyte_name: Bulk Density, Compliant Cavity, Field Moisture
analyte_desc: Bulk density (compliant cavity at field H20) is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume measured at field (sampling) moisture content by the compliant cavity method. It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.
1/3 bar water, reconstituted moist is the gravimetric percent water in reconstituted samples (held moist) after equilibration at 1/3 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.

Bulk density, <2mm fraction, reconstituted, oven dry is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume measured on oven dry (105 C) reconstituted samples. It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.

Bulk density, <2mm fraction, reconstituted, 1/3 bar is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume measured on reconstituted samples at 1/3 bar water tension. It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.
2 bar water, cores is the gravimetric percent water in soil core after equilibration at 2 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.
1/3 bar water, cores is the gravimetric percent water in soil core after equilibration at 1/3 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.
1/10 bar water, cores is the gravimetric percent water in soil core after equilibration at 1/10 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.
1 bar water, cores is the gravimetric percent water in soil core after equilibration at 1 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.
0.06 bar water, cores is the gravimetric percent water in soil core after equilibration at 0.06 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.

Bulk density, <2 mm fraction, 1/10 bar is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume being measured after equilibration at 1/10 bar water tension. It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.
1/3 bar water, clods is the gravimetric percent water in natural fabric (clods) after equilibration at 1/3 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.
1/10 bar water, clods is the gravimetric percent water retained at 1/10 bar tension. It is measured on natural fabric (clods), and reported on a <2 mm base.
1 bar water, clods, <2mm is the gravimetric percent water in natural fabric (clods) after equilibration at one bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.
0.06 bar water, <2mm fraction of clods is the gravimetric percent water held by clods equilibrated at 0.06 bar water tension. It is reported on a <2 mm base.

Bulk density, oven dry (105 C) is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume measured on oven dry (105 C) natural fabric (clods). It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.

Bulk density, <2 mm fraction, 1/3 bar is the weight per unit volume of the <2 mm fraction, with volume being measured after equilibration at 1/3 bar water tension. It is reported as grams per cubic centimeter on a <2 mm base.
Atterberg plastic limit is the water content of a soil at the boundary between the plastic and brittle states. It is defined by the ASTM D 4318 test.

Atterberg liquid limit is the gravimetric percent water content of the soil at a defined boundary between the liquid and plastic states. It is determined by ASTM method D 4318 and reported as percent water on a <0.4 mm base.
Aggregate stability is the weight percent of 0.5mm - 2mm aggregates remaining after wet sieving.
